<html>
<body>
  <b>1. git config --global user.name "" </b> - Setting your Git username for every repository on your computer
  <br>
  <b>Example: </b> git config --global user.name "Mona Lisa"
  <br><br>
  <b>2. git reset HEAD </b> git-reset - Reset current HEAD to the specified state
  <br>
  -HEAD is the pointer to the current branch reference, which is in turn a pointer to the last commit made on that branch.
  <br><br>
  <b>3. gitk -all </b> gitk - The Git repository browser. Displays changes in a repository or a selected set of commits. This includes visualizing the commit graph, showing information related to each commit, and the files in the trees of each revision.
  <br>
  --all - Show all refs (branches, tags, etc.).
  <br><br>
  <b>4. git branch --merged </b> - See which branches are already merged into the branch you re on.
  <br><br>
  <b>5. git branch "branch" "commit hash"</b> - instantly commit hash of the chosen "branch"
  <br><br>
  <b>6. git pull "remote" "branch" </b> - Fetch the specified remotes copy of the chosen "branch" and immediately merge it into the local copy.
 The "remote" repository is the source of a fetch or pull operation.
  <br><br>
  </body>
</html>
